# Cairn counterfactual memory — b2b_quotes.yml TEMPLATE
#
# Copy this file to b2b_quotes.yml and edit it. b2b_quotes.yml is
# gitignored so you can name real clients and numbers without
# leaking commercial-sensitive material into the repo.
#
# This file holds named B2B quote histories — the decisions you made
# when pricing bespoke commercial work, who you were pricing it for,
# what options you offered, which one the client took (or didn't),
# and what you learned. It mirrors disputes.yml with three differences:
#
#   1. Every row is written with needs_privacy_scrub=True so the
#      pipeline runs the regex PII pass over the context before it
#      lands in the DB. Commercial counterparty names are fine in
#      the DB; individual email addresses, phone numbers, postcodes
#      and VAT numbers get redacted automatically.
#
#   2. Cases without a verbatim lesson get a Claude Sonnet lesson
#      (not Opus). B2B quotes are high-volume-high-signal; disputes
#      are low-volume-highest-signal, which is why disputes get Opus.
#
#   3. Phases are usually singular — one quote goes out, one outcome
#      comes back. The multi-phase structure is available for long
#      negotiations but most quotes only need phase: quote_sent.
#
# Field reference
# ---------------
#   case_id                    Required. kebab-case. Unique within file.
#                              Usually client-something-YYYY.
#   client                     Optional string. The client name —
#                              passed into the email enrichment hook
#                              and stored in raw_source_ref.client.
#   quote_value_gbp            Optional number. Stored for report queries.
#   phases                     Required. Usually one phase per case.
#     phase                    Required. snake_case label.
#     decided_at               Required. ISO date like 2024-09-10
#     context                  Required. Situation, client, budget,
#                              the tension that made this a decision.
#                              3–8 sentences.
#     chosen_path              Required. Which quote you actually led with.
#     rejected_alternatives    Optional but VALUABLE. List the other
#                              options you considered and the reason
#                              each one was wrong for THIS client.
#                              The canonical shape is a three-option
#                              quote: cheap / middle / premium.
#     outcome                  Optional. Accepted? Rejected? Ghosted?
#     chosen_path_score        Optional. -1.0 (disaster) to +1.0 (clear win).
#     metrics                  Optional mapping. margin_pct, days_to_decision,
#                              referrals_materialised, whatever you can
#                              measure.
#   lessons_in_your_own_words  Optional. Attached VERBATIM to the last
#                              phase's outcome. If blank, Sonnet (not
#                              Opus) generates a lesson instead.

# ── Worked example 1: canonical three-option quote ──────────────────
- case_id: bakery-barn-2024
  client: Bakery Barn
  quote_value_gbp: 2400
  phases:
    - phase: quote_sent
      decided_at: 2024-09-10
      context: |
        An independent bakery wanted a new illuminated shopfront sign.
        The budget ceiling was firm and they were shopping around
        three local signmakers. We presented three options: cheapest
        (foamex only), middle (aluminium tray with vinyl graphics),
        and premium (built-up illuminated letters).
      chosen_path: "Led with the middle option at exactly their budget ceiling, framed the other two as context."
      rejected_alternatives:
        - path: "Lead with the foamex-only option"
          reason: "Would not have lasted two winters outdoors in Northumberland — short-term saving, long-term complaint."
        - path: "Lead with the premium built-up letters"
          reason: "40% over their stated budget; would have got us rejected on price before the quality argument landed."
      outcome: |
        Client accepted the middle option and paid the deposit within
        a week. Installed six weeks later without incident.
      chosen_path_score: 0.9
      metrics:
        margin_pct: 38
        days_to_decision: 6
  lessons_in_your_own_words: |
    For small independent clients with a firm budget, anchor on the
    middle of three options and design that option to land EXACTLY
    at their ceiling. The cheap option exists to prove you've
    listened; the premium option exists to make the middle feel
    sensible. You are not trying to sell the cheap or the premium.

# ── Worked example 2: quote that went cold (Sonnet will write a lesson) ──
- case_id: hair-salon-discount-2024
  client: Tyneside Hair Salon
  quote_value_gbp: 1200
  phases:
    - phase: quote_sent
      decided_at: 2024-11-20
      context: |
        A small hair salon pushed for a 25% discount in exchange for
        vague promises of future referrals. The quote was already at
        a thin margin for a one-off installation.
      chosen_path: "Held full price and offered a small goodwill extra (discount on a future service) instead of cutting the quote."
      rejected_alternatives:
        - path: "Accept the 25% discount for the referral promise"
          reason: "Would have set an undercutting precedent and the referral promise is rarely redeemed in practice."
      outcome: |
        Client signed at full price. No referrals materialised over
        the next six months.
      chosen_path_score: 0.5
      metrics:
        discount_requested_pct: 25
        discount_given_pct: 0
        referrals_received: 0
  # lessons_in_your_own_words intentionally omitted — Sonnet will
  # distil the lesson from the context + outcome.

# ── Worked example 3: quote you walked away from ────────────────────
- case_id: hotel-chain-six-site-2025
  client: Regional Hotel Chain
  quote_value_gbp: 85000
  phases:
    - phase: scoping_call
      decided_at: 2025-02-08
      context: |
        A national hotel chain enquired about rebranding six regional
        sites simultaneously. The opportunity looked lucrative but the
        timeline was impossible and the specification kept shifting
        mid-quote. Three scope changes in the first week alone.
      chosen_path: "Declined the full six-site job and offered to pilot one site first at a fixed price."
      rejected_alternatives:
        - path: "Accept all six sites with heavy contingency pricing"
          reason: "Scope was too unstable to price honestly; contingency would have to be 30%+ which kills the win-rate."
      outcome: |
        Client declined the pilot offer and went to a larger competitor.
        Trade gossip six months later suggested that competitor ran
        significantly over time and over budget on the same job.
      chosen_path_score: 0.6
  lessons_in_your_own_words: |
    When scope is unstable, a fixed-price pilot on ONE deliverable
    is the honest answer. If the client won't accept a pilot, that
    IS the signal — the full job is a trap. The margin on saying
    "no" is often higher than the margin on saying "yes" to an
    unpriced scope.

